16
00:01:52,650 --> 00:01:53,883
No, thank you.

17
00:01:53,883 --> 00:01:54,716
- Why not?

18
00:01:54,716 --> 00:01:55,645
- Too much salt.

19
00:01:55,645 --> 00:01:56,478
- How do you know?

20
00:01:56,478 --> 00:01:57,311
You haven't even tried it.

21
00:01:57,311 --> 00:01:58,144
- It's always too much salt.

22
00:01:58,144 --> 00:01:58,977
- I'll get you something to drink.

23
00:01:58,977 --> 00:02:00,300
- No, thank you.

24
00:02:00,300 --> 00:02:02,220
- How about I put some
music on the stereo?

25
00:02:02,220 --> 00:02:04,170
- No, thank you.

26
00:02:04,170 --> 00:02:06,180
(chuckling)
You wanna talk.

27
00:02:06,180 --> 00:02:07,548
- Very perceptive.
- Mm-hmm.

28
00:02:07,548 --> 00:02:08,920
- What would I do without you, huh?

29
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:10,410
- Hm, eat too much
popcorn, too much butter,

30
00:02:10,410 --> 00:02:11,243
too much--
(groans)

31
00:02:11,243 --> 00:02:12,750
- I wanna ask you something.

32
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:16,260
You don't think that I'm shallow, do you?

33
00:02:18,640 --> 00:02:20,715
- It doesn't sound like
you have much choice.

34
00:02:20,715 --> 00:02:21,548
(Sam chuckles)

35
00:02:21,548 --> 00:02:23,980
You know, it's a decision made
by the board of directors.

36
00:02:23,980 --> 00:02:25,570
But don't you have a say as a partner?

37
00:02:25,570 --> 00:02:26,770
- No, no, no.

38
00:02:26,770 --> 00:02:28,600
Look, I don't mind
working for another firm.

39
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:31,450
I'm happy to do a good deed for the city.

40
00:02:31,450 --> 00:02:32,700
It doesn't even bother
me nobody's gonna make

41
00:02:32,700 --> 00:02:34,070
any money on this deal, but you know,

42
00:02:34,070 --> 00:02:36,320
they teamed me up with an
architect I've never met,

43
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:37,640
from some company I've never heard of.

44
00:02:37,640 --> 00:02:39,228
The guy's supposed to be
some kind of a lunatic.

45
00:02:39,228 --> 00:02:40,061
(TV chatters)

46
00:02:40,061 --> 00:02:42,455
- He's an architect, how
much of a lunatic can he be?

47
00:02:42,455 --> 00:02:45,040
- (grunts) NB, he goes by
the initials NB, right?

48
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:47,560
He works out of some kind
of an abandoned garage.

49
00:02:47,560 --> 00:02:49,800
I get to see, he lives
in a tent up on the roof.

50
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:52,240
- Well, you always say
architecture's about change.

51
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:55,340
- Yeah, well architecture can
change all at once, all right?

52
00:02:55,340 --> 00:02:56,960
I'd like to do my good deed for the city

53
00:02:56,960 --> 00:03:00,060
without turning my life inside
out, thank you very much.

54
00:03:00,060 --> 00:03:02,662
(Sam grunts)

55
00:03:02,662 --> 00:03:04,740
And the board says, "Well,
we can't work in a garage,

56
00:03:04,740 --> 00:03:06,780
so we'll make space for
him and some of his people

57
00:03:06,780 --> 00:03:08,580
on your floor, starting this week."

58
00:03:08,580 --> 00:03:10,480
We're not jammed up enough down there.

59
00:03:11,324 --> 00:03:14,006
(Sam groans)

60
00:03:14,006 --> 00:03:14,839
- What?

61
00:03:14,839 --> 00:03:17,523
- I think you might be a
teeny, tiny bit shallow.

62
00:03:18,382 --> 00:03:21,408
- (sighs) Let's talk about something else.

63
00:03:21,408 --> 00:03:22,419
- Fine.

64
00:03:22,419 --> 00:03:23,433
- Sex.

65
00:03:23,433 --> 00:03:25,223
- You wanna talk about sex?

66
00:03:25,223 --> 00:03:28,470
- (groans) When's Zoey coming home?

67
00:03:28,470 --> 00:03:29,303
- Tomorrow. (kisses)

68
00:03:29,303 --> 00:03:31,570
- Ah, that should be enough time.

69
00:03:31,570 --> 00:03:34,128
- Let's make some noise.
(chuckles)

70
00:03:34,128 --> 00:03:36,461
(kisses)
Mm.

71
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:41,660
Well, all I can do is give you my opinion.

72
00:03:42,567 --> 00:03:43,400
(phone rings)
No, no,

73
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:46,430
you're absolutely right,
(stammers) it's totally subjective.

74
00:03:46,430 --> 00:03:48,230
Yeah.
(phone rings)

75
00:03:48,230 --> 00:03:50,730
All right, well look, we
wanna wish you the best.

76
00:03:50,730 --> 00:03:52,320
All right, yeah, sure. (phone clicks)

77
00:03:52,320 --> 00:03:54,300
What do you wanna bet they go
through a dozen architects,

78
00:03:54,300 --> 00:03:55,400
they'll still hate the building?

79
00:03:55,400 --> 00:03:56,233
- No bet.

80
00:03:56,233 --> 00:03:57,927
Chairman of the Asian Heritage Council.

81
00:03:57,927 --> 00:03:58,760
- (sighs) Yeah.

82
00:03:58,760 --> 00:03:59,593
- And--

83
00:03:59,593 --> 00:04:00,942
- Wait, wait, wait, what is it?

84
00:04:00,942 --> 00:04:02,020
These are the calls
just from this morning?

85
00:04:02,020 --> 00:04:03,250
- Friday; the chairman's--

86
00:04:03,250 --> 00:04:04,420
- Well, why didn't I see them on Friday?

87
00:04:04,420 --> 00:04:05,570
- Because you weren't here.

88
00:04:05,570 --> 00:04:06,403
- Where was I?

89
00:04:06,403 --> 00:04:08,522
- You were playing golf
with Elisa at Meadowlands.

90
00:04:08,522 --> 00:04:09,355
- Yeah, that's right.
(phone rings)

91
00:04:09,355 --> 00:04:10,380
- Well, you know, memory loss is part

92
00:04:10,380 --> 00:04:11,490
of the normal aging process.

93
00:04:11,490 --> 00:04:12,760
- Well, thank you for sharing that.

94
00:04:12,760 --> 00:04:14,383
I'm sorry, what's your name again?

95
00:04:15,410 --> 00:04:17,240
All right, fellas, let's start

96
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:19,290
with the chairman of the Asian, whatever.

97
00:04:25,570 --> 00:04:27,570
- Crap, crap, crap.
(phone rings)

98
00:04:27,570 --> 00:04:29,350
- [Elisa] Something wrong, Bess?

99
00:04:29,350 --> 00:04:30,710
- I bet if I had sex more often,

100
00:04:30,710 --> 00:04:32,170
I wouldn't be so disorganized.

101
00:04:32,170 --> 00:04:33,003
- Really?

102
00:04:33,003 --> 00:04:35,020
I didn't know there was a
correlation between, what is it?

103
00:04:35,020 --> 00:04:38,450
Frequency of intercourse and
organizational skills? (laughs)

104
00:04:38,450 --> 00:04:39,440
- Go ahead, laugh.

105
00:04:39,440 --> 00:04:41,680
You're married to a man who
can't keep his hands off you.

106
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:42,570
Look at your desk.
(chuckles)

107
00:04:42,570 --> 00:04:44,430
I'm married to a guy who
pats me on the shoulder

108
00:04:44,430 --> 00:04:48,000
every fiscal quarter, and I
just scheduled two school tours

109
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,250
on the same day, at the same time.

110
00:04:50,250 --> 00:04:51,960
- Bring me the paperwork,
I'll see what I can do.

111
00:04:51,960 --> 00:04:53,090
- Don't you think you oughta stop

112
00:04:53,090 --> 00:04:54,480
this volunteer saint routine

113
00:04:54,480 --> 00:04:55,830
and take the paying job they're offering?

114
00:04:55,830 --> 00:04:58,420
- If I take the paying job,
I have less flexibility.

115
00:04:58,420 --> 00:04:59,253
- [Bess] And a bigger office.

116
00:04:59,253 --> 00:05:00,480
- And that means less time with Sam!

117
00:05:00,480 --> 00:05:02,020
Besides, I hear they
already hired somebody.

118
00:05:02,020 --> 00:05:04,020
- They hired someone else for your job?

119
00:05:04,020 --> 00:05:05,580
- Bess, this is my job.
(phone rings)

120
00:05:05,580 --> 00:05:07,510
And I have more than enough work to do,

121
00:05:07,510 --> 00:05:08,920
so why don't you get me your paperwork

122
00:05:08,920 --> 00:05:10,830
so I can get back to mine?

123
00:05:10,830 --> 00:05:13,290
- In 30 years, I never understood you.

124
00:05:13,290 --> 00:05:15,408
- [Employee] Metropolitan Art Museum.

125
00:05:15,408 --> 00:05:16,241
(upbeat piano music)

126
00:05:16,241 --> 00:05:17,610
- Yeah, you're absolutely right, Zoey.

127
00:05:17,610 --> 00:05:19,270
You are treated differently
because you're my daughter.

128
00:05:19,270 --> 00:05:21,273
Anybody else who was this
late would have been fired!

129
00:05:21,273 --> 00:05:23,773
(phone rings)

130
00:05:24,992 --> 00:05:26,483
Look, I'm not saying that it's--

131
00:05:26,483 --> 00:05:28,076
- Dad, I got the message!

132
00:05:28,076 --> 00:05:30,070
- You're the only intern
we have around here.

133
00:05:30,070 --> 00:05:31,420
You happen to be my daughter,
it just doesn't look good.

134
00:05:31,420 --> 00:05:33,960
- Okay, okay, okay, okay!

135
00:05:33,960 --> 00:05:34,793
How do I look?

136
00:05:34,793 --> 00:05:37,170
- You look fine, how do I look?

137
00:05:37,170 --> 00:05:39,305
- Uptight, (sighs) as usual.

138
00:05:39,305 --> 00:05:40,879
(sighs)
Hi, how are you?

139
00:05:40,879 --> 00:05:42,334
- Zoey!
- How are you?

140
00:05:42,334 --> 00:05:46,536
(talking over each other)
- Guys, sorry we're late.

141
00:05:46,536 --> 00:05:49,536
(jazzy piano music)

142
00:06:30,427 --> 00:06:34,630
(sniffs)
(phone rings)

143
00:06:34,630 --> 00:06:36,690
- Maybe I should call again.

144
00:06:36,690 --> 00:06:38,260
- Why don't we just reschedule?

145
00:06:38,260 --> 00:06:39,900
I really, I have a lot of stuff that uh--

146
00:06:39,900 --> 00:06:43,348
- NB!
(phone clatters)

147
00:06:43,348 --> 00:06:44,181
(door slams)
(panting)

148
00:06:44,181 --> 00:06:45,860
- Very late and very sorry.

149
00:06:45,860 --> 00:06:47,068
- You're a woman.

150
00:06:47,068 --> 00:06:49,110
- Yeah. (pants)

151
00:06:49,110 --> 00:06:50,780
There was an old man, crossing

152
00:06:50,780 --> 00:06:52,330
on the crosswalk in front of my car.

153
00:06:52,330 --> 00:06:54,740
One minute he was upright,
the next minute he was down.

154
00:06:54,740 --> 00:06:56,777
I dialed 911, four firetrucks arrived

155
00:06:56,777 --> 00:06:59,870
and the paramedics started
treating him for heart failure.

156
00:06:59,870 --> 00:07:01,232
Turned out, he had gas.

157
00:07:01,232 --> 00:07:03,180
(employees laugh)

158
00:07:03,180 --> 00:07:05,840
I'm Nell Bergen, a woman.

159
00:07:05,840 --> 00:07:07,573
You must be Sam Mercer, the man.

160
00:07:08,413 --> 00:07:09,247
(phone rings)

161
00:07:09,247 --> 00:07:10,847
- Ah, this is my daughter, Zoey.

162
00:07:11,970 --> 00:07:13,400
- How do you do? (sighs)

163
00:07:13,400 --> 00:07:14,250
You're an architect?

164
00:07:14,250 --> 00:07:16,170
- Yeah no, actually she's our new intern.

165
00:07:16,170 --> 00:07:17,440
- Well, an aspiring architect.

166
00:07:17,440 --> 00:07:19,170
- She's a sociology major at Brown.

167
00:07:19,170 --> 00:07:20,980
She's taking a semester off.

168
00:07:20,980 --> 00:07:21,833
- Can she talk?

169
00:07:23,180 --> 00:07:25,010
- As a matter of fact, I can.

170
00:07:25,010 --> 00:07:27,270
My field is urban social dynamics.

171
00:07:27,270 --> 00:07:29,370
- Good, well when you
graduate, you can come and work

172
00:07:29,370 --> 00:07:30,360
at the center we design.
- Hm.

173
00:07:30,360 --> 00:07:31,920
- It's gonna be really terrific,

174
00:07:31,920 --> 00:07:33,800
and I don't just mean the way it looks.

175
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:35,810
You've met my assistant, David Su.

176
00:07:35,810 --> 00:07:38,430
Miss Cora Windsor, who
of course is very modest,

177
00:07:38,430 --> 00:07:41,730
but in truth came up with the
entire idea for the center.

178
00:07:41,730 --> 00:07:43,973
- Nell had some good ideas, as I recall.

179
00:07:45,550 --> 00:07:47,630
- So what did you talk
about before I arrived?

180
00:07:47,630 --> 00:07:51,210
- The uh, Lovell House, Neutra, 1927.

181
00:07:51,210 --> 00:07:54,610
- Ah, very close, but it
took two years to build.

182
00:07:54,610 --> 00:07:57,180
Completion date was 1929.

183
00:07:57,180 --> 00:07:59,620
If this project is as
successful as we hope,

184
00:07:59,620 --> 00:08:02,310
it could become a model for
community centers nationwide.

185
00:08:02,310 --> 00:08:03,200
- Really?

186
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:05,380
- Yes.
(papers rustle)

187
00:08:05,380 --> 00:08:07,410
Don't you know about the center?

188
00:08:07,410 --> 00:08:09,780
- No, not much, not really.

189
00:08:09,780 --> 00:08:12,892
Don't your interns get
briefed on ongoing projects?

190
00:08:12,892 --> 00:08:15,440
- (grunts) Well, usually they do but--

191
00:08:15,440 --> 00:08:17,250
- Wait, aren't you the
one who never turned up

192
00:08:17,250 --> 00:08:19,600
for any of the meetings
we had on this project?

193
00:08:21,730 --> 00:08:23,358
- I guess I must be.

194
00:08:23,358 --> 00:08:25,634
(chuckles)
- Hm.

195
00:08:25,634 --> 00:08:26,467
(Zoey chuckles)

196
00:08:26,467 --> 00:08:29,570
- Well, on the face of it, it's
a regular recreation center

197
00:08:29,570 --> 00:08:31,190
but applicants have to attend classes,

198
00:08:31,190 --> 00:08:32,860
given on the premises at no charge,

199
00:08:32,860 --> 00:08:34,760
designed to teach life lessons.

200
00:08:34,760 --> 00:08:37,100
When a member has completed
all the classes offered,

201
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:39,960
they can remain at the center
by becoming a volunteer.

202
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:42,410
- Wow, that sounds really great.

203
00:08:42,410 --> 00:08:46,380
- What is not clear to
me is how you get a feel

204
00:08:46,380 --> 00:08:48,560
of what needs to happen architecturally

205
00:08:48,560 --> 00:08:49,840
when you haven't the faintest idea of

206
00:08:49,840 --> 00:08:52,090
what the structure you're
designing is about.

207
00:08:54,170 --> 00:08:57,170
(jazzy piano music)

208
00:09:05,210 --> 00:09:07,720
- She's not that weird.

209
00:09:07,720 --> 00:09:09,818
Nell is (stammers) dynamic.

210
00:09:09,818 --> 00:09:11,880
- Dynamic, she's a
dynamic pain in the ass.

211
00:09:11,880 --> 00:09:12,713
She's been there for a week.

212
00:09:12,713 --> 00:09:14,180
She's rearranged the coffee room already.

213
00:09:14,180 --> 00:09:15,180
- Everyone says it's better.

214
00:09:15,180 --> 00:09:17,580
- Uh-huh, well, she
put these humongous set

215
00:09:17,580 --> 00:09:19,220
of stereo speakers in her office.

216
00:09:19,220 --> 00:09:21,041
- She uses music as an inspiration.

217
00:09:21,041 --> 00:09:22,070
- Oh. (scoffs)

218
00:09:22,070 --> 00:09:23,550
- She, a lot of people do!

219
00:09:23,550 --> 00:09:24,970
Zack does it when he sky dives.

220
00:09:24,970 --> 00:09:26,350
- Oh, I see. (stammers)

221
00:09:26,350 --> 00:09:27,905
She wears napkins in her hair.

222
00:09:27,905 --> 00:09:28,738
- What? (laughing)

223
00:09:28,738 --> 00:09:31,950
- They're not napkins,
Dad, they're bandanas.

224
00:09:31,950 --> 00:09:33,350
- They're napkins, okay?

225
00:09:33,350 --> 00:09:34,830
I saw him 'em at Bess and Murray's picnic.

226
00:09:34,830 --> 00:09:36,020
We used 'em to wipe our mouth,

227
00:09:36,020 --> 00:09:36,853
they're napkins.
- Okay.

228
00:09:36,853 --> 00:09:39,080
- Look, (stammers) she's got her own style

229
00:09:39,080 --> 00:09:41,030
and she's successful.
(knife clicks)

230
00:09:41,030 --> 00:09:42,140
And she wasn't wrong about you missing

231
00:09:42,140 --> 00:09:43,910
those community meetings, either.

232
00:09:43,910 --> 00:09:45,600
- Oh, she wasn't, huh?

233
00:09:45,600 --> 00:09:47,893
- I wouldn't mind being
like her when I grow up.

234
00:09:48,890 --> 00:09:49,920
- Oh now, that's a hell of a thing to say

235
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:50,974
right here in front of your mother.

236
00:09:50,974 --> 00:09:52,780
- Oh.

237
00:09:52,780 --> 00:09:55,090
- Dad, there are other women
in the world besides Mom.

238
00:09:55,090 --> 00:09:57,781
- I love it when you two talk
about me like I'm not here.

239
00:09:57,781 --> 00:10:01,370
- (scoffs) Besides, I
didn't say Nell was better.

240
00:10:01,370 --> 00:10:02,615
She's just different.

241
00:10:02,615 --> 00:10:03,448
(Sam scoffs)

242
00:10:03,448 --> 00:10:06,160
- Yeah, she really is or she tries to be?

243
00:10:06,160 --> 00:10:07,230
- Aha.

244
00:10:07,230 --> 00:10:10,180
- She doesn't see things
like other people, you know?

245
00:10:10,180 --> 00:10:12,570
She's, (stammers) I don't know, real...

246
00:10:12,570 --> 00:10:14,180
alive!
- Hmm.

247
00:10:14,180 --> 00:10:15,640
- You'd like her, mom.

248
00:10:15,640 --> 00:10:17,810
- Oh yeah, yeah, you'd love her.

249
00:10:17,810 --> 00:10:20,015
- She thinks Dad's a stuffy old fart.

250
00:10:20,015 --> 00:10:20,853
- Zoey!

251
00:10:21,770 --> 00:10:24,737
I've known that about
your father for years.

252
00:10:24,737 --> 00:10:26,650
(chuckling)
- Hey, hey, hey, hey!

253
00:10:29,400 --> 00:10:31,390
- How do we know this
isn't just some showcase

254
00:10:31,390 --> 00:10:33,700
for your businesses to come
in here, put up a bunch

255
00:10:33,700 --> 00:10:36,920
of walls and hang plaques
of who donated what?

256
00:10:36,920 --> 00:10:37,753
- You don't.

257
00:10:37,753 --> 00:10:40,130
Which is why you all need
to muster up some trust,

258
00:10:40,130 --> 00:10:42,620
mix it with some
responsibility, and participate

259
00:10:42,620 --> 00:10:44,910
in this project so walls
of plaques don't happen.

260
00:10:44,910 --> 00:10:47,848
- A lot of promises made to
this community been broken.

261
00:10:47,848 --> 00:10:49,080
- Yeah, tell 'em.
- That's right!

262
00:10:49,080 --> 00:10:53,670
- Hold it, now, nobody up
here is denying the fact

263
00:10:53,670 --> 00:10:56,680
that this community has been treated badly

264
00:10:56,680 --> 00:10:58,362
for too many years.
- Mm-hmm.

265
00:10:58,362 --> 00:10:59,195
(crowd murmurs)

266
00:10:59,195 --> 00:11:02,660
Just as nobody up here
can absolutely guarantee

267
00:11:02,660 --> 00:11:04,580
that every promise that you've heard today

268
00:11:04,580 --> 00:11:06,100
is going to be kept.

269
00:11:06,100 --> 00:11:06,933
- That's what I'm sayin'!

270
00:11:06,933 --> 00:11:08,250
- But I will promise you this.

271
00:11:08,250 --> 00:11:10,470
This recreation center
is going to be built.

272
00:11:10,470 --> 00:11:12,893
- Yeah, right.
- Which is why we're here.

273
00:11:13,800 --> 00:11:16,330
I mean, we're here because
we want your participation.

274
00:11:16,330 --> 00:11:17,560
We want your ideas.

275
00:11:17,560 --> 00:11:20,150
We want your comments,
we want your complaints.

276
00:11:20,150 --> 00:11:21,430
We want your help.
(siren wails)

277
00:11:21,430 --> 00:11:25,030
Now, I don't know if this
suggestion has been made yet

278
00:11:25,030 --> 00:11:27,920
because I missed the earlier meetings,

279
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:30,190
for which I apologize.
(crowd murmurs)

280
00:11:30,190 --> 00:11:32,370
Suppose we set up a
separate telephone line

281
00:11:32,370 --> 00:11:35,470
and we plaster the phone number
all over the neighborhood.

282
00:11:35,470 --> 00:11:37,150
Right, then if anybody's got any ideas

283
00:11:37,150 --> 00:11:39,020
or comments or criticisms, all they have

284
00:11:39,020 --> 00:11:41,913
to do is pick up the phone and call it in.

285
00:11:43,810 --> 00:11:45,496
What do you think?

286
00:11:45,496 --> 00:11:47,483
(talking over each other)
- I don't know.

287
00:11:47,483 --> 00:11:50,566
- I think it's a great idea.
- Uh-huh.

288
00:11:57,055 --> 00:12:00,230
(car sputters)

289
00:12:00,230 --> 00:12:01,125
- [Nell] Try it again.

290
00:12:01,125 --> 00:12:01,958
- 'Kay.

291
00:12:03,181 --> 00:12:06,140
(car sputters)

292
00:12:06,140 --> 00:12:06,973
No.

293
00:12:06,973 --> 00:12:08,370
- [Nell] Ah, I'm gonna need a tow.

294
00:12:08,370 --> 00:12:10,320
- Okay, I'll see if I can find a phone.

295
00:12:12,486 --> 00:12:16,088
- Wa-hoo!
(truck rumbles)

296
00:12:16,088 --> 00:12:18,838
(brakes screech)

297
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:25,990
Hey, sweet thing.
(country music)

298
00:12:25,990 --> 00:12:26,823
Nice wheels.

299
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:31,010
- Thanks, you think so?

300
00:12:31,010 --> 00:12:33,083
- I'm a parts expert, I know so.

301
00:12:33,980 --> 00:12:35,160
- Well I ought to tell you,

302
00:12:35,160 --> 00:12:37,820
I'm not interested in a casual liaison.

303
00:12:37,820 --> 00:12:41,120
I'm looking for a serious,
long-term commitment.

304
00:12:41,120 --> 00:12:42,303
Are you interested?

305
00:12:43,480 --> 00:12:46,992
- Let's go, Luther.
(truck rumbles)

306
00:12:46,992 --> 00:12:50,313
- (laughs) Works every time.

307
00:12:52,873 --> 00:12:55,290
(hood slams)

308
00:12:57,650 --> 00:12:59,557
I'm starved, let's eat.

309
00:12:59,557 --> 00:13:02,495
(Sam sighs)

310
00:13:02,495 --> 00:13:04,912
(calm music)

311
00:13:06,001 --> 00:13:08,084
Mm, excellent, thank you.

312
00:13:09,310 --> 00:13:11,000
- You always eat other people's food?

313
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:11,833
- Well, if they offer.

314
00:13:11,833 --> 00:13:13,590
Is your wife always out at dinner time?

315
00:13:14,440 --> 00:13:15,580
- Uh, my wife's at a meeting.

316
00:13:15,580 --> 00:13:19,270
She's a volunteer at the museum,
and she's a gourmet cook.

317
00:13:19,270 --> 00:13:22,279
- I'm a horrible cook,
but I'm a gourmet eater.

318
00:13:22,279 --> 00:13:24,010
(chuckles)
- Mm.

319
00:13:24,010 --> 00:13:25,290
After ruling out some places that

320
00:13:25,290 --> 00:13:26,810
should probably be closed
to health authorities,

321
00:13:26,810 --> 00:13:29,160
I finally found great
takeout 'round the office.

322
00:13:29,160 --> 00:13:30,450
- Oh, (chuckles) you like takeout?

323
00:13:30,450 --> 00:13:32,600
- Yep, I love takeout.

324
00:13:32,600 --> 00:13:34,953
And working late, and small adventures.

325
00:13:38,824 --> 00:13:40,550
(Sam clears throat)

326
00:13:40,550 --> 00:13:42,110
- If you appreciate things
that are young and tender,

327
00:13:42,110 --> 00:13:44,560
the baby squid is excellent,
would you like some?

328
00:13:45,990 --> 00:13:47,706
Thanks for the lift, by the way.

329
00:13:47,706 --> 00:13:48,539
- Uh, it's okay.

330
00:13:52,427 --> 00:13:55,883
And I have to say that those gentlemen,

331
00:13:58,000 --> 00:13:59,853
well, they weren't wrong about you.

332
00:14:00,980 --> 00:14:05,980
Wheels, uh, legs.
(chuckles)

333
00:14:08,660 --> 00:14:10,893
- Well, here's to conflict resolution.

334
00:14:12,650 --> 00:14:14,540
Architectural and otherwise.

335
00:14:16,032 --> 00:14:20,076
(crowd chatters)
(glasses clink)

336
00:14:20,076 --> 00:14:23,481
(both slurping)

337
00:14:23,481 --> 00:14:24,314
- Ah.

338
00:14:30,252 --> 00:14:33,752
(bright percussive music)

339
00:14:37,683 --> 00:14:40,200
Workin' late on a Friday.

340
00:14:40,200 --> 00:14:41,033
- You're working, too.

341
00:14:41,033 --> 00:14:46,033
- Ah, well, Zoey and her mother

342
00:14:46,360 --> 00:14:49,535
are on kind of a ladies' night out.

343
00:14:49,535 --> 00:14:51,293
You know, so here I am.

344
00:14:51,293 --> 00:14:53,360
- That was a very
interesting lecture you gave

345
00:14:53,360 --> 00:14:55,290
at the library last week.

346
00:14:55,290 --> 00:14:57,838
- Oh, thank you, I didn't see you there.

347
00:14:57,838 --> 00:14:59,170
- Well, I was draped in black.

348
00:14:59,170 --> 00:15:01,613
Didn't want you to be
distracted by my legs.

349
00:15:01,613 --> 00:15:05,000
- Uh-huh. (chuckles)

350
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:07,570
Tell me something, you
really like this music?

351
00:15:07,570 --> 00:15:10,623
I mean, that's surprises me. (snickers)

352
00:15:11,580 --> 00:15:13,590
- What surprises me is
that we're working together

353
00:15:13,590 --> 00:15:16,250
on a rather large project,
and you don't have the,

354
00:15:16,250 --> 00:15:18,803
the slightest clue about my
work or what it means to me.

355
00:15:19,640 --> 00:15:21,530
- Well then, why don't you tell me?

356
00:15:21,530 --> 00:15:22,680
- Why don't I show you?

357
00:15:24,936 --> 00:15:25,980
- Are we going somewhere?

358
00:15:25,980 --> 00:15:27,533
- Yep.
(bright percussive music)

359
00:15:27,533 --> 00:15:30,283
A visit to a genuine
architectural treasure.

360
00:15:32,184 --> 00:15:33,017
(stereo clicks off)

361
00:15:33,017 --> 00:15:34,895
- Ah, that's much better.

362
00:15:34,895 --> 00:15:36,596
I bet you like rap music too, right?

363
00:15:36,596 --> 00:15:38,300
- (chuckles) Absolutely,
especially the ones

364
00:15:38,300 --> 00:15:40,793
about judgmental, male architects.

365
00:15:44,857 --> 00:15:47,720
(crickets chirping)

366
00:15:47,720 --> 00:15:52,720
(gate creaks)
(dog barks distantly)

367
00:15:53,032 --> 00:15:58,032
(gentle acoustic music)
(laughing)

368
00:16:03,559 --> 00:16:04,570
(crickets chirping)

369
00:16:04,570 --> 00:16:06,020
I sneak in here all the time.

370
00:16:08,263 --> 00:16:10,203
I found a reference to it in a book.

371
00:16:11,070 --> 00:16:15,620
Took me forever to find it.
(leaves crackle)

372
00:16:15,620 --> 00:16:18,770
Used to be huge, then they
developed the property

373
00:16:18,770 --> 00:16:20,170
and this is all that's left.

374
00:16:24,330 --> 00:16:26,640
There's nothing else
like it from the period,

375
00:16:26,640 --> 00:16:27,820
which from the materials used

376
00:16:27,820 --> 00:16:29,893
and some of the building techniques,

377
00:16:29,893 --> 00:16:32,673
I think it's probably about 30 years old.

378
00:16:35,160 --> 00:16:37,440
Sam, when I work, my feelings come first.

379
00:16:37,440 --> 00:16:39,090
From them come design and theory.

380
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:42,553
For me, this place has a solid feeling.

381
00:16:44,140 --> 00:16:46,260
Design and theory are definitely here,

382
00:16:46,260 --> 00:16:47,793
but I bet they came last.

383
00:16:49,720 --> 00:16:51,050
- Actually, it's 32 years.

384
00:16:51,050 --> 00:16:51,883
- Hm?

385
00:16:54,073 --> 00:16:57,572
- It was a competition to
design a park for an urban lot.

386
00:16:57,572 --> 00:16:59,100
(Sam chuckles)

387
00:16:59,100 --> 00:17:01,620
I was 20, I was a lot more
interested in the cash prize

388
00:17:01,620 --> 00:17:05,220
than in expressing my feelings,
but I'm glad you like it.

389
00:17:05,220 --> 00:17:06,720
- Get out of here.

390
00:17:09,233 --> 00:17:11,410
This is your treasure?

391
00:17:11,410 --> 00:17:12,243
- Swear to God.

392
00:17:14,230 --> 00:17:16,615
It's too bad they kinda let it go.

393
00:17:16,615 --> 00:17:19,198
(gentle music)

394
00:17:22,240 --> 00:17:23,540
You really live in a tent?

395
00:17:25,123 --> 00:17:26,566
- I used to.

396
00:17:26,566 --> 00:17:29,805
(Sam chuckles)

397
00:17:29,805 --> 00:17:32,888
(bright piano music)

398
00:17:56,440 --> 00:17:59,357
(thoughtful music)

399
00:18:01,530 --> 00:18:06,530
(hurried footsteps)
(gate creaks)

400
00:18:14,120 --> 00:18:14,953
- Sam?

401
00:18:16,432 --> 00:18:17,265
Sam!

402
00:18:18,415 --> 00:18:22,885
Sam, you're late!
(heels clicking)

403
00:18:22,885 --> 00:18:23,965
- Ah, yeah, okay.

404
00:18:23,965 --> 00:18:24,798
- Are you all right?

405
00:18:24,798 --> 00:18:25,756
- Yeah, I'm fine, yeah.

406
00:18:25,756 --> 00:18:27,978
- (sighs) Just do me a favor.

407
00:18:27,978 --> 00:18:29,390
It took me a long time
to get used to living

408
00:18:29,390 --> 00:18:31,060
with the most punctual man on Earth.

409
00:18:31,060 --> 00:18:32,680
Don't change on me now.

410
00:18:32,680 --> 00:18:33,870
Mother's making you breakfast.

411
00:18:33,870 --> 00:18:35,700
Come on, hurry up, it's gonna get cold!

412
00:18:35,700 --> 00:18:38,164
Come on. (pats)
- Okay, okay, okay!

413
00:18:38,164 --> 00:18:41,331
(weatherman chatters)

414
00:18:48,978 --> 00:18:51,107
(sighs)
(TV zaps)

415
00:18:51,107 --> 00:18:51,940
- Where's Zoey?

416
00:18:51,940 --> 00:18:52,773
- I don't know, why?
(scoffs)

417
00:18:52,773 --> 00:18:53,670
She said she was stuck.

418
00:18:53,670 --> 00:18:55,520
You know, everybody is a
little off this morning.

419
00:18:55,520 --> 00:18:57,660
- I hope I'm not included in that review.

420
00:18:57,660 --> 00:18:59,220
- If you don't overcook Sam's eggs.

421
00:18:59,220 --> 00:19:01,430
He is late, ooh, is he cranky.

422
00:19:01,430 --> 00:19:03,050
- Could be male menopause.

423
00:19:03,050 --> 00:19:04,023
- Excuse me.
- Mm!

424
00:19:04,940 --> 00:19:06,090
I saw it on "Oprah," this man

425
00:19:06,090 --> 00:19:06,923
was in terrible shape.
- Mother,

426
00:19:06,923 --> 00:19:09,440
Sam does not have male menopause.

427
00:19:09,440 --> 00:19:10,380
- Who's got menopause?

428
00:19:10,380 --> 00:19:12,710
- Nobody has menopause, eat, eat, eat!

429
00:19:12,710 --> 00:19:15,086
- Good morning, everybody.
- Ah, my Lord.

430
00:19:15,086 --> 00:19:17,300
- Oh, you do lay the best eggs, Janet,

431
00:19:17,300 --> 00:19:19,230
but I don't have time.
- Oh, Sam.

432
00:19:19,230 --> 00:19:20,680
- Coffee, that's what I need.

433
00:19:21,590 --> 00:19:22,470
Waggin', Zo-Zo.

434
00:19:22,470 --> 00:19:26,010
- You know, it would be different
if you weren't my father.

435
00:19:26,010 --> 00:19:27,370
- What would it be different?

436
00:19:27,370 --> 00:19:28,470
- Being late.

437
00:19:28,470 --> 00:19:30,879
I mean, it's not a
crime, Zoey, it's just--

438
00:19:30,879 --> 00:19:34,570
- Zo, Zo, move your ass.

439
00:19:34,570 --> 00:19:35,883
Bye everybody, see ya later.

440
00:19:35,883 --> 00:19:38,790
- Hey, hey, hey, what
about my goodbye kiss?

441
00:19:38,790 --> 00:19:41,090
- [Janet] It's important for
families to eat together.

442
00:19:41,090 --> 00:19:44,195
It helps children bond to their parents.

443
00:19:44,195 --> 00:19:45,028
- [Elisa] Bye!

444
00:19:47,514 --> 00:19:49,453
- (sighs) Fine.

445
00:19:52,724 --> 00:19:57,724
(phone rings)
(employees chatter)

446
00:19:59,800 --> 00:20:01,580
- Oh, here he comes now, just a moment.

447
00:20:01,580 --> 00:20:04,580
Sam, there's a Mr. Bentley who
would like to speak with you.

448
00:20:08,577 --> 00:20:12,400
- Boy, you certainly have a lot of awards.

449
00:20:12,400 --> 00:20:15,080
- It's not my idea. (mutters)

450
00:20:15,080 --> 00:20:18,130
My, my wife decorated my office and uh,

451
00:20:18,130 --> 00:20:19,830
what can I say, she's proud of me.

452
00:20:21,403 --> 00:20:22,236
(intercom beeps)

453
00:20:22,236 --> 00:20:23,620
- [Phyllis] Sam, a contractor,
Mr. Bentley is here.

454
00:20:23,620 --> 00:20:25,691
He says he won't leave
until he can speak to you.

455
00:20:25,691 --> 00:20:27,893
- (sighs) Just tell him I'm not here.

456
00:20:29,370 --> 00:20:30,540
Uh, look...

457
00:20:32,633 --> 00:20:33,806
Look, I think that we uh--

458
00:20:33,806 --> 00:20:37,160
(knocking)
(sighs)

459
00:20:37,160 --> 00:20:38,640
- He saw you come in.

460
00:20:38,640 --> 00:20:41,400
Also there's a presentation in
the board room in 20 minutes.

461
00:20:41,400 --> 00:20:42,947
- If that's Nick Bentley, just tell him

462
00:20:42,947 --> 00:20:45,120
I'm the other architect on the project.

463
00:20:45,120 --> 00:20:46,370
I think he'll go quietly.

464
00:20:47,393 --> 00:20:48,226
(phone rings)

465
00:20:48,226 --> 00:20:49,763
- And close the door, Phyllis.

466
00:20:53,630 --> 00:20:55,420
- He botched up a job of mine.

467
00:20:55,420 --> 00:20:57,130
I almost had to get his license revoked.

468
00:20:57,130 --> 00:20:58,723
So you better stay on my good side.

469
00:21:01,685 --> 00:21:04,268
(Sam chuckles)

470
00:21:05,263 --> 00:21:09,430
- I'm a happily married
man, that's why I stopped.

471
00:21:13,240 --> 00:21:14,840
I've never met anybody like you.

472
00:21:17,860 --> 00:21:21,130
Obviously, I find you (sighs)

473
00:21:21,130 --> 00:21:22,933
very attractive and very smart and,

474
00:21:24,530 --> 00:21:26,200
if things were different--

475
00:21:26,200 --> 00:21:28,360
- I was married once
for a couple of minutes.

476
00:21:28,360 --> 00:21:29,620
He was a poet.

477
00:21:29,620 --> 00:21:32,523
He wrote about our marriage
instead of participating in it.

478
00:21:33,700 --> 00:21:35,340
Being the only child of two dead parents,

479
00:21:35,340 --> 00:21:36,610
I sort of thought having a husband

480
00:21:36,610 --> 00:21:38,683
might be good company, but I was wrong.

481
00:21:40,850 --> 00:21:42,300
Anyway, I'm glad you stopped.

482
00:21:43,310 --> 00:21:44,210
It's not my style.

483
00:21:47,660 --> 00:21:49,965
I almost never sleep--

484
00:21:49,965 --> 00:21:52,730
- (knocking) Hi!

485
00:21:52,730 --> 00:21:54,123
- With interns' fathers.

486
00:21:55,500 --> 00:21:59,339
- If I forgot anything, I'm
gonna kill myself. (sighs)

487
00:21:59,339 --> 00:22:00,560
Hi, Nell.
- Hi.

488
00:22:00,560 --> 00:22:01,493
- Nice shoes!

489
00:22:02,720 --> 00:22:03,920
Like 'em, Dad?

490
00:22:03,920 --> 00:22:06,180
- Yeah, yeah, I liked 'em when I wore 'em

491
00:22:06,180 --> 00:22:08,590
in the service too.
(laughs)

492
00:22:08,590 --> 00:22:10,090
- I wear 'em 'cause I like 'em.

493
00:22:10,090 --> 00:22:10,923
- Good.

494
00:22:12,440 --> 00:22:17,203
- Listen, uh, I have
work to do, so if you...

495
00:22:21,058 --> 00:22:22,260
(phone rings)
- Bye.

496
00:22:22,260 --> 00:22:23,570
- [Sam] Bye!

497
00:22:23,570 --> 00:22:24,720
- [Zoey] Dad said you grew up in Europe.

498
00:22:24,720 --> 00:22:25,910
- [Nell] Yeah, have you been?

499
00:22:25,910 --> 00:22:27,280
- [Zoey] No, not yet.

500
00:22:27,280 --> 00:22:29,066
- Oh, at your age, you should go.

501
00:22:29,066 --> 00:22:34,066
(phone rings)
(employees chatter)

502
00:22:35,292 --> 00:22:37,792
(door creaks)

503
00:22:39,430 --> 00:22:40,880
- [Zoey] Who died?

504
00:22:40,880 --> 00:22:43,080
- Huh, what do you mean?

505
00:22:43,080 --> 00:22:45,690
- Well, it looks like a funeral inside.

506
00:22:45,690 --> 00:22:48,420
- [Elisa] Oh no, your
father brought me flowers.

507
00:22:48,420 --> 00:22:51,100
- Yeah, it's an old fashioned
custom between men and women,

508
00:22:51,100 --> 00:22:53,209
Zo, you wouldn't know anything about it.

509
00:22:53,209 --> 00:22:55,680
It's before Zack's time.

510
00:22:55,680 --> 00:22:58,180
- How come you got flowers
if you're going out of town?

511
00:22:58,180 --> 00:23:01,140
Oh Mom, Nell Bergen
was wearing these shoes

512
00:23:01,140 --> 00:23:03,440
that Dad could not handle.

513
